turns: Hillary Clinton's security team arrived at a fruit processing plant in Iowa with a second Scooby van, a GMC vehicle with a nearly identical Secret Service escort vehicle. The vans have raised roofs, deep-tinted windows, and New York license plates. While the original van has a mustard-yellow tag, the second has blue and white plates. Clinton often receives constant protection because she is part of a former first family. A mother of six has asked for help after a fire in Georgia destroyed her rented condo, which had been their home for four years, leaving her and her children without any belongings. Kalimah Dixon managed to get her children out of the condo safely, but it was reduced to a pile of rubble. She is currently unemployed and has been unable to find a lease for a new home while being homeless. The American Red Cross has assisted her in her search for a place to live, but shelters have turned her away, and she has started a GoFundMe page to raise money. Dixon is worried about her children as they have to take a standardized test on Tuesday, and she doesn't know where they will be on Monday.

Australian couple abandoned a boy born in a surrogacy deal in India and were repeatedly told the child would be left stateless. Documents reveal the couple sought citizenship for a baby girl while leaving her twin brother behind. The Australian High Commission in India and Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade were aware of the illegal surrogacy arrangement involving the couple. The case has raised concerns over international surrogacy and the commercialization of children.

Kecil, a one-year-old orangutan, was rejected by his mother and two surrogate mothers. However, he was given a chance at a new life when he was adopted by Maggie, a 53-year-old experienced mother, at Chicago's Brookfield Zoo. After ten months of being cared for by Maggie, the two have bonded and Kecil is set to make his first public appearance this weekend.

Paris Saint-Germain midfielder Javier Pastore has rejected ex-Manchester United player Eric Cantona's claim that he is the best player in the world, saying that Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him. Cantona had praised Pastore earlier this month saying he watched two Paris Saint-Germain games just to see him play and that he had something special. But speaking ahead of his side's Champions League tie against Barcelona in the Nou Camp, Pastore believes Messi and Ronaldo are a level above him.

A midwife has won a decade-long battle to change the guidelines on how soon newborns' umbilical cords should be clamped after birth. Amanda Burleigh believed that clamping the cord within seconds of delivery was unnatural and potentially harmful, and she collected evidence to support her case. NICE has now changed its guidelines to state that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord earlier than one minute after the birth of the baby, and that the cord should be clamped within five minutes of birth, with the option of leaving it longer if the mother requests. The change allows mothers to hold their babies for a moment while still connected to them. Dr Hutchon, a retired obstetrician, said that hospitals had blindly clamped and cut within seconds of birth for decades, but there was continual resistance to change, with some doctors refusing delayed cord-clamping even today.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to show no mercy if French peacekeepers are found guilty of sexually assaulting starving children in the Central African Republic. Fourteen soldiers have been accused of abusing children in exchange for food, and an investigation has been underway since last year. The French defence ministry denies covering up the scandal, and has launched a probe into the case after receiving a leaked UN report. The UN employee who leaked the report was suspended, and investigators conducted a probe into serious allegations of child abuse and sexual exploitation by French troops. If true, the allegations are "horrible and unacceptable," says a government member who wished to remain anonymous.

A Texas pastor's wife, Aracely Meza, has been arrested for attempting to resurrect a two-year-old boy who had died. Meza was charged with injury to a child by omission for her role in the ritual, during which she used oils and prayed while trying to bring the boy back to life. The boy's mother is not Meza, and the incident occurred at a home that also served as a church. Meza and her husband, who are pastors, presided over church services at the residence, and other families, including the two-year-old's, lived there as well. The ceremony allegedly took place on March 22, and Meza was arrested on Monday.

Professional snooker players John Higgins and Graeme Dott, both from Scotland, won their first-round matches at the 2023 Betfred World Championship on Sunday. John Higgins, a four-time champion, defeated Robert Milkins 10-5, while Graeme Dott, a former champion, defeated Ricky Walden 10-8. Both players expressed confidence in their abilities and mentioned the possibility of winning the tournament, although Higgins seemed to doubt his chances earlier in the interview.

Despite their matching denim attire, they were pleased with the result and put the win down to little details. Their teammate, Jeremy Mathieu, admitted that the side were not at their best and blamed the international break for the poor display. However, they still managed to secure the victory, with the French defender praised his defensive partner, Gerard Pique, and the Brazilian players on their game-winning victory.

It is reported that Chelsea manager Jose Mourinho is considering a summer move for Atletico Madrid midfielder Koke. Technical Director Michael Emenalo has been spotted at Atletico's match on Saturday to watch Koke play. Mourinho is reportedly willing to offer Atletico's Filipe Luis as a makeweight in the deal. Koke has a high release clause of £50 million and has been instrumental for Atletico, reaching the Champions League final last season. Mourinho is looking to add to a midfield that has looked tired at times this season.

Tom Ballard, a professional climber, plans to climb K2 mountain after 20 years since his mother died while descending from its peak. Alison Hargreaves, his mother, was the second person to climb Mount Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen but passed away in 1995 during her descent from K2. Tom was only six years old at the time. Despite the criticism that his mother faced for climbing dangerous mountains while raising a young family, she shrugged off the flak. Tom has clear memories of climbing when he was a child and has followed in his mother's footsteps. He plans to solo climb all six of the great north faces of the Alps in the winter season and is now training for K2.

It is claimed that there is trillions of pounds worth of oil beneath an area of England known as 'Britain's Dallas', which is dubbed the Weald Basin. Analysis suggests that there is up to 100 billion barrels of oil reserves in the Weald Basin, which could meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years. UK Oil & Gas Investments has discovered 100 billion barrels worth of oil reserves in the Weald Basin, which is located across Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire and Kent. However, experts remain sceptical of the claims and one described them as "overly optimistic". The Weald Basin holds up to 15 billion barrels of shale oil, according to a study by Imperial College London. The British Geological Survey has estimated the Weald Basin holds just 4.4 billion barrels of shale oil. The oil could be extracted from the Weald Basin using fracking, but only a fraction of the oil may be accessible for extraction and significant volumes may be required. The UK government owns the land under the homes in the Weald Basin, meaning homeowners would not receive any profits from the oil found beneath their homes. Oil companies pay the government for an annual license to extract the oil and keep the profits.

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls in Somerset and Gloucestershire. The BVA concluded that the first two years of culling had not demonstrated conclusively that ‘controlled shooting’ of free-running badgers could be effective and humane. The BVA still supports badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. The Environment Secretary promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Tories win the election. She criticized Labour for pledging to give up on culling. Ms Truss said the Government's strategy included cattle movement controls, vaccination in 'edge' areas around disease hotspots, and culling where the disease is rife. Animal welfare campaigners welcomed the news but said the BVA’s ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting was ‘regrettable’. The chief vet admitted the benefits of the cull in Gloucestershire might not be realized due to the challenges of protest groups.

It is stated in the text that modern technology, such as social media and smartphones, can create more pitfalls in budding relationships than it does benefits. Women are also sometimes tempted to spend too much time in the bathroom and people fall victim to the temptation of getting in touch too quickly after their date. The article also suggests ways to avoid showing oneself up on a date, such as leaving conversations about dating apps to evenings with friends, not taking pictures of food for Instagram, and not immediately changing relationship status on Facebook. The article ends by suggesting that it is important to keep taxi apps handy, use Snapchat to update friends and not to brag about Tinder matches, memes, or assume companion’s preferences.

Tottenham Hotspur will face Aston Villa in a Premier League match at White Hart Lane on Sunday, January 18. A mother decides to give birth prematurely to her sick daughter who had developed a serious form of Spina Bifida. The daughter, Annabelle, is born weighing just 290 grams at Canberra Hospital and dies of her undeveloped lungs. The parents contact Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organization dedicated to turning donated wedding gowns into outfits for babies who pass away too soon. Angel Gowns delivers a replica dress for the family to have in their house and the mother says she looks at it every day to remember her daughter.

A black police constable in Wiltshire, UK, has won a race discrimination case against his police force after he was singled out for being black and passed over for promotion. Mr. Lungu was initially retaliated against by his colleagues after he raised concerns internally and had negative comments made about him based on his color, ultimately leading him to be treated poorly and eventually denied a promotion. The employment tribunal found that Mr. Lungu was unlawfully discriminated against based on race, and the Chief Constable of Wiltshire Police stated that the force was "concerned" about the findings and would take lessons from the case. Wiltshire Police currently has only 16 ethnic minority officers out of a total of over 1,000, and Mr. Lungu's case is being seen as a wake-up call for the force to take seriously complaints of discrimination and harassment.

A parent taught their baby daughter how to suck on a plastic water bottle, as shown in a video that has been viewed over 190,000 times on YouTube. The baby quickly learned the trick and the two of them enjoyed some bonding time together with the props.

A unique set of photographs taken nearly 100 years before much of the historic center of the city of Bristol was destroyed by Nazi bombing have surfaced, captured by photographer Hugh Owen between 1850 and 1855. The images show various areas of Bristol, such as the waterfront, city center, St Mary Redcliffe church, and buildings like The Fourteen Stars Tavern, which was pulled down in 1857. The shots show how much the city has changed, particularly around High Street, but some areas like St John's Gate at the Church of St John the Baptist have remained largely unchanged. The pictures are expected to be auctioned tomorrow and could fetch up to £30,000.

Atletico Madrid has taken advantage of Valencia's dropped points to move up to third place in the standings with their 2-0 win over Cordoba in the Primera Division. France forward Antoine Griezmann scored both goals for Atletico, his 15th and 16th of the season, with the second coming from Saul Niguez, who had been out injured. Valencia now sits in fourth place, two points behind Atletico but with a game in hand. The teenager, who is believed to have a three-year-old son, was rushed to Good Hope Hospital in Sutton Coldfield, West Midlands, where she was placed in a coma before dying a week later. The investigation into the teenager's death is ongoing, and police are waiting for the results of a post-mortem examination.

A Tokyo playground has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, with readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour. Japanese authorities have cordoned off the park and set up a health advice office to answer concerns from local residents. The cause of the radiation is still unknown, but it may be coming from something buried under the park. The city is conducting further testing to determine the type and source of the radiation. Concerned parents and citizens have been measuring radiation levels in schools and parks in Japan since the 2011 Fukushima disaster.

Amir Khan believes Kell Brook is only calling him out to have the "one big payday" that has eluded him during his 10-and-a-half year career. A Dallas architect, Matt Mooney, has built a stunningly modern 3,700-square-foot three-bedroom home using 14 shipping containers. The home, named "PV14," features a 40ft long swimming pool on the ground floor, a 1,400 sq ft roof deck with a 360 degree view of White Rock Lake and downtown Dallas, and a 2-story glass-paneled tower overlooking the pool. All the ceilings were left exposed, and columns were placed around the house to restore structural integrity to the materials. The upstairs levels are outfitted with maple wood floors to complement the views of the nearby park and lake, and deep porches protect the home from direct sunlight while still allowing natural light to seep in.

It is expected that Jordon Ibe will sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool by the end of the week. The 19-year-old has impressed since returning to Liverpool this season and will keep him at Anfield until 2020. Rik Mayall, a comedian known for his roles in "The New Statesman" and other comedy shows, did not leave a valid will, which could result in his family facing inheritance tax issues. Even though Mayall suffered from epilepsy and almost died in a quad bike accident, he did not update his will after the accident. Mayall's personal estate would be divided according to Government intestacy rules, which take into account marital status and children. Mayall's children may inherit an amount liable for inheritance tax if the amount is more than the inheritance tax limit of £325,000. Mayall's widow would have received a life interest in the remaining half, meaning she could not touch or transfer that money but could claim interest on it. Mayall's family could seek to avoid the tax by drawing up a deed of variation to split up his estate, reducing any sum left to the children so it was below the tax threshold. Mayall's writing partner, Laurence Marks, also lived in the Oxfordshire constituency of Witney, where David Cameron became MP in 1997. Marks had become a local celebrity due to the success of The New Statesman. Marks and his partner Maurice Gran were introduced to all five candidates for the Witney seat at the 2001 general election, and they plumped for an ambitious young man called David Cameron, who won the seat with a majority of nearly 8,000. Cameron sent the pair a handwritten letter after becoming prime minister, thanking them for backing him in 2001 and saying, "Thank you so much, I wouldn’t be here without you two."

A group of passengers, mainly Indian nationals and others who had been working in Yemen's capital, Sanaa, boarded an Air India plane as soon as buses brought them to the airport. They were evacuating due to the ongoing fighting in the city. The passengers carried small suitcases and duffel bags, leaving larger bags behind. They were evacuated to Djibouti in a small window when Saudi planes weren't bombing the city. The Air India crew offered drinks as if they were on a vacation flight, but some passengers were already asleep from exhaustion. The Indian government had evacuated over 2,500 people from Yemen in the last few days, with flights going to Djibouti or through boats at port cities. People were leaving behind much more than luggage, including Yemeni Professor Damodar Thakur who had lived in Sanaa for 34 years and loved it there, the war had caused many to leave without stopping to collect their belongings.

A new study in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the MMR vaccine and autism, even among high-risk children. The study, which was conducted on approximately 95,000 young people and focused on children with older siblings who have autism, found no increased risk of autism associated with vaccination. This study adds to the numerous other studies conducted over the past 15 years that have consistently found no link between the MMR vaccine and autism. Despite the consistent results from these studies, concerns over vaccine safety persist, particularly among parents who have children with autism. This may partially explain why children with autistic siblings are less likely to be vaccinated. However, the data is clear that there is no signal to suggest a relationship between MMR and the development of autism in children, regardless of whether they have a sibling who has autism.

Chelsea midfielder Cesc Fabregas will wear a special protective face mask after breaking his nose in a game against Stoke City. Andros Townsend's wonder strike in England's 1-1 draw with Italy in Turin on Tuesday night silenced his critics, including former player Paul Merson. This has been a challenging season for Townsend, but England manager Roy Hodgson continued to trust him, which paid off with a successful performance against Juventus.

A husband accused of attempting to murder his cheating wife wrote to her from prison while on remand, asking her to gather his belongings for his trial. He asked for a blue suit and three ties that would go with it, as well as a decent jumper and beige casual jacket. The UK is to open its first three proton beam therapy centres, thanks to a company called Proton Partners International. The centres will be available to NHS cancer patients and will be operational in Cardiff, London, and Northumberland by 2017. The first centre in Cardiff is expected to open next year. Proton beam therapy is a highly-targeted type of radiotherapy that can treat hard-to-reach cancers, such as spinal tumours, with a lower risk of damaging the surrounding tissue and causing side effects. The King family, who obtained proton beam therapy for their five-year-old son Ashya who suffered from brain cancer, inspired the formation of Proton Partners International. The government is also creating two NHS proton beam therapy units which will open in 2018.

It is reported that ambulance bosses in the UK are traveling to Australia to hire paramedics due to a shortage of trained staff. Biso the cat, who had been trapped in a wall at the Mohamed Naguib metro station in Cairo for five years, has finally been freed. The cat's survival was thanks to an elderly man named Uncle Abdo, who would feed him scraps of food every day. The cat's plight came to the attention of animal activists when a picture of his tail was posted on Facebook. Animal rights activists, including Ms Shehata, Elgebaly and el-Kordy, went to the station to rescue the cat. However, Biso escaped before they could catch him.

At least 35 workers were killed at a dairy factory in Yemen when it was struck by Saudi Arabian airstrikes targeting Shiite rebel positions in both the north and the south of the country. The ongoing Saudi-led campaign to defeat the Iran-backed rebels is now in its seventh day. Saudi Arabia hinted that it was prepared to launch a ground invasion in Yemen to force the Houthis to allow current president Abed Rabbo Mansour Hadi to return to the country. Witnesses reported that the factory's anti-aircraft guns returned fire before the factory was set ablaze and parts of its main building collapsed from explosions, with many workers still inside. Two military officials said the factory had been used as a rebel weapons cache, and that while the airstrikes flattened the warehouses, the main factory building was only partially destroyed - suggesting it might have been hit from ground. All officials and witnesses spoke on condition of anonymity because they were not authorized to speak to the media. The airstrikes come as Saudi Arabia hinted that it might carry out a ground invasion in Yemen in the coming days. The Saudi-led air campaign may be accompanied by an operation on the ground, a Saudi Arabian official said, adding that the Houthis are moving from one place to another in search of safe havens. Scores of Yemeni expatriates in Tehran held a protest and burned photos of Saudi King Salman.

A truck crash on an elevated highway in Boston caused delays for hundreds of morning commuters who were affected by the incident. The collision occurred between the Interstate 93 southbound and the subway and rail tracks in the Dorchester neighborhood, resulting in non-life-threatening injuries for both the truck driver and the car driver. Replacement shuttle buses were run to accommodate the southbound passengers, causing long queues to form. The incident caused headaches for locals trying to get to work, even after the truck was towed by crane. State troopers are still investigating the incident, and no charges have been filed.

It is important that Arsenal decide whether or not to sign goalkeeper Petr Cech from Chelsea at the end of the season. Frankie Dettori will not ride for Sheik Joaan Al Thani's Al Shaqab Racing in France this summer, with the contract instead going to Gregory Benoist. Benoist will ride most of Al Shaqab's horses in France, and Thierry Jarnet will continue to ride dual Arc winner Treve. Frankie Dettori will focus on the British flat season. Sheikh Joaan Al Thani made the decision as it is logistically no longer feasible to have one jockey cover both countries due to expanding operations. Richard Hannon's Ivawood and Estidhkaar both entered the Greenham Stakes at Newbury. Charlie Hills-trained Connection, Acomb Stakes winner, put in a good gallop ahead of the Guineas. AP McCoy will ride at Ayr and then retire at Sandown's end-of-season meeting.

Lois Lilienstein, known for her role as a co-star on the Canadian preschool TV show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show," has passed away at the age of 78. Lilienstein, who was diagnosed with a rare form of cancer last year, died peacefully from her disease in Toronto last Wednesday night. She was born in Chicago in 1936 and moved to Toronto in 1996 with her son and husband. "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show" ran on both the CBC in Canada and Nickelodeon in the US from 1984 to 1995 and was best known for its songs like "Skinnamarink" and "Peanut Butter." Sally Catto, general manager of programming at CBC Television, paid tribute to Lilienstein, stating, "Sharon, Lois and Bram got their start at CBC back in the '80s with the Elephant Show, and they went on to become icons to children all across North America through various programs and specials. Lois will be fondly remembered by her many friends at CBC."

French freediver Guillame Néry filmed a video in 2010 at Dean’s Blue Hole in the Bahamas, the deepest so-called 'blue hole' in the world with an underwater entrance. The video shows Néry jumping into the hole without scuba gear and holding his breath to reach the bottom, although he didn't go all the way to the bottom. He practices breath-holding exercises and follows a diet to increase lung capacity. Competitive breath-holders push their mind-body control techniques to the limits to breathe without scuba gear. Stig Severinsen, nicknamed The Man Who Doesn't Breathe, holds the record for the longest time breath held voluntarily by a male.

A suicide bombing attack in Jalalabad, Afghanistan, killed 33 people and injured over 100 others. The ISIS terrorist group claimed responsibility for the attack, making it the first in Afghanistan by ISIS. The Taliban denied any involvement. The incident took place during rush hour when government workers were collecting their pay at a bank. UN condemned the violence and expressed fears about ISIS' involvement in the region.

Laura Wells has launched a new eco-friendly swimwear line called Reef Runway, which is made entirely of 100% recycled materials. The line includes one and two-piece suits, ranging from sizes 10 to 24, and is inspired by the ocean and coral reef scenes. The Australian model and environmental scientist collaborated with Swimsuits For All to create the collection.

The TrackYourDose app is a new iOS app available for £1.49 ($1.99) that allows users to track their personal radiation exposure from medical examinations, changes in location, and flights. The app uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists from the Physikalisch-Technische Bundesanstalt (PTB) in Germany and the University Oulu, Finland. This model has been developed since 1997 and uses a carry-on "flight case" used to measure radiation levels in various locations and flight altitudes. The app also tracks other types of radiation such as gamma and neutron radiation and calculates the ambient dose equivalent. The app accounts for radiation exposure on the ground and from medical examinations, including X-rays and CT scans, in addition to cosmic radiation from air travel.

Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility that officials had previously connected to a foodborne illness linked to the deaths of three people. The company has recalled 10 products made at its Brenham, Texas, plant, which is not currently shipping products and has not received any product since March 13. The recall is the first in the company's 108-year history, and patients at a hospital in Kansas became ill with listeriosis after drinking shakes made with Blue Bell ice cream. The CDC identified six patients with listeriosis between 2010 and 2014 that was indistinguishable from that found in the 3-ounce cup ice cream product traced to the Oklahoma plant. The company said it will conduct a careful and complete examination of its Oklahoma plant 'to determine the exact cause of the contamination.' The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has been notified of the company's decision to voluntarily shut down the plant. Systems

Jon Hamm, a Golden Globe-winning actor known for his role in Mad Men, was involved in a hazing incident at the Sigma Nu fraternity while attending the University of Texas at Austin in 1990. According to court documents, Hamm and seven other frat brothers allegedly set fire to a pledge, beat him with a paddle, and traumatized him in various brutal ways as part of a hazing ritual. The pledge later went to the police to report the incident. The incident caused the fraternity to shut down and led to Hamm facing charges for assault and hazing. Hamm was charged in 1991, but he eventually reached a plea deal with the authorities and the charges were dismissed. The case shockingly resurfaced as a result of legal documents and pictures from the time. The hazing incident had a significant impact on Hamm, both at the time and later when he played Don Draper on the TV show Mad Men, which led him to seek help and enter rehab in 2017.

The UK government has dismissed the threat of prosecution against oil and gas firms working off the Falkland Islands, which are claimed by Argentina. Argentina's President Cristina Fernandez de Kirchner had threatened legal action against British and US companies exploring for oil in the region. The diplomatic row over the Falklands has worsened in recent weeks, with Argentina promising to see the islands form part of its territory again. The UK Foreign Secretary has said that Cristina Kirchner's threats against those who do business with the Falkland Islands are hollow and illegal, and the UK will protect the islands from Argentinian bullying.

Delta Flight 2522 landed at LaGuardia Airport with an odor of smoke reported by the crew. Emergency workers surrounded the MD-88 twin-engine plane and firefighters on full protective suits used a thermal imaging camera to locate a heat source inside the plane. The odor was detected moments after landing, and the crew shut down both engines and alerted the fire department. Passengers remained on the plane for about 45 minutes until the firefighters located the potential heat source and the plane was taken out of service for an inspection. The fire department spokesperson said the safety of the customers and crew was always the top priority, and the plane was brought to the gate where customers deplaned normally.

David Luiz, the Brazilian defender for Paris Saint-Germain, injured his hamstring in a match against Marseille on Sunday, and has taken to Instagram to show off a new hairstyle in the form of a man bun, calling himself a "Parisien." His teammate Lucas Moura also posted a picture with Luiz, poking fun at his new hairstyle. While Luiz's injury will keep him out for at least four weeks and potential missing eight league matches, his team will aim to defend their Ligue 1 and Champions League glory without him.

US President Barack Obama has said that diplomacy is the best option to deal with Iran's contested nuclear program. He has hailed the framework agreement reached with Iran as a "historic understanding" and said he is convinced talks are the best way forward. He also confirmed that the US will continue to keep Congress apprised of the "substance of the deal," as there will be a "robust debate" on the agreement in the US. However, his Israeli counterpart, Benjamin Netanyahu, has criticized the deal, stating that it would threaten the survival of the state of Israel.

A 12-year-old girl with Leukemia has been kicked out of her private Catholic school because of low attendance and poor academic performance. The school made accommodations for her illness, but it did not improve her attendance, and she only attended school 32 days out of the entire year. Her parents feel that the school failed their child and filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights. Rose's mother says that even though her daughter is no longer receiving cancer treatment, her recovery will take some time. The school did not elaborate on what kind of accommodations were made, but the family believes that they were inadequate for Rose's serious diagnosis. Rose was hoping to return to school next year, but now she is unsure where she will go to school. Despite this, Rose has plenty of support from family and friends and is determined to raise money for St. Baldricks to find a cure for childhood cancer.

Passive smoking affects plants and can transfer nicotine from contaminated soil and plumes of smoke. Researchers found that nicotine levels in peppermint plants were significantly elevated after fumigation with cigarette smoke. Dogs whose owners smoke are more likely to develop cancer and cats that live with smokers are more likely to develop Feline Lymphoma, a serious cancer of the blood and immune system. The widespread occurrence of nicotine in medicinal, spice and food plants may, at least in part, be due to other nicotine sources apart from the illegal use of insecticides. The findings shed light on the hitherto unexplained success behind farming practices such as crop rotation and the co-cultivation of certain vegetables.

The video shows two male chameleons engaging in a brief, aggressive battle over a female mate. The more aggressive of the two chameleons is shown launching a fierce attack on the other chameleon, resulting in the defeated chameleon wriggling in pain as it tries to escape. The video captures the intensity of the battle and the aggression displayed by the chameleons as they battle for dominance. The video maker provides play-by-play commentary in French throughout the battle.

Scotland youth international Jack Cosgrove has agreed to join Edinburgh rugby club on a two-year deal starting next season. The 20-year-old Worcester Warriors prop has been capped nine times for the Dark Blues Under 20s side. Cosgrove said he is excited to join the club, which recently reached the European Cup final, and looks forward to improving his game and contributing to the team.

Aaron Hernandez, a former New England Patriots player who was sentenced to life in prison without parole for the 2013 murder of Odin Lloyd, has been given the prisoner number "W106228" and is being held in maximum security at the Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center. Hernandez was known to smoke "angel dust," a hallucinogenic drug, in marijuana cigarettes, and his behavior became increasingly aggressive and paranoid as a result of its use. Hernandez had a history of violence, including being charged with two murders, one of which he is currently on trial for.

It appears that Manchester City manager Manuel Pellegrini has stated that the club's Academy players are not yet ready to step into the first team, including Jason Denayer who has impressed on loan at Celtic this season. As a result, Celtic may face an uphill battle to retain Denayer's services, as City plans to invest in "homegrown" talent. Denayer falls into this category despite being from Belgium, making him an attractive option for City next season. Pellegrini has said that he will be patient with the young players and may bring back some loaned professionals to fill the gaps in the first team.

Ander Herrera, a Manchester United midfielder, revealed in a Q&A video that he wears his full name on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons. He used the name from his time at Athletic Bilbao and had a good spell in his debut season there. He has been playing well for Manchester United and has been added to the starting lineup by Louis van Gaal. Herrera scored twice in a recent match against Aston Villa, which has raised the team's spirits.

Despite losing 6-1 in the first leg of their Champions League quarter-final against Bayern Munich, Porto's supporters gave the team a hero's welcome upon their return to Portugal. The team had been unbeaten in the tournament until the match on Tuesday night, but Bayern put six goals past them and Porto fell 7-4 in the aggregate. However, Porto's coach, Julen Lopetegui, said his team can be proud of their run in the tournament and accepted defeat against a superior team. Porto's fans celebrated their achievement in reaching the quarter-finals for the first time since the 2008-09 season.

The BBC has been criticized for making a computer game simulating the terrifying ordeal of Syrian refugees trying to flee their war-torn country. The game, titled "Syrian Journey," is available on the BBC website and places players in the shoes of refugees trying to escape Syria and make it to Europe. The game often ends badly for the players, with grim outcomes such as being separated from family, being sold to militia groups, and dying in the Mediterranean. Critics have called the game inappropriate and tasteless, among other things, and some have accused the BBC of turning the suffering of millions into a "children's game."

Boston marathon bombing victim's family and couple oppose death penalty for Dzhokar Tsarnaev and call for life in prison without parole instead.
Last week, the family of 8-year-old victim Martin Richard and a married couple who lost a leg each in the attack in 2013, urged the jury not to sentence Tsarnaev to death. They pleaded for a life in prison sentencing without parole to ensure that Tsarnaev 'disappears from our collective consciousness as soon as possible.' Their appeal was made one day after the two-year anniversary of their son's death. Two years ago, Tsarnaev, 21, rolled a bomb through crowds of people at the finish line of the Boston Marathon, killing four people and wounding more than 260. His older brother Tamerlan died in a shootout with police days later. Tsarnaev's federal trial is currently under way and a jury will decide whether to sentence him to death or life in prison without parole.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife who claimed half of his $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement was reached just before a court ruling on whether Giray could be named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company. Ulukaya disputed Giray's claim of family loans used to start his business, and the settlement was reached to avoid losing assets worth $1 billion to Giray. Even though the suit was settled, Ulukaya still faces business problems as Chobani considers replacing him as CEO due to a product recall and negative financial results in 2013.

Diego Costa has suffered a hamstring injury and is likely to miss Chelsea's upcoming games against QPR and Manchester United. He is expected to be back in two weeks, just in time for Chelsea's crunch clash against Arsenal, which could determine the outcome of the title race. Costa's manager Jose Mourinho is being cautious with the player's return and will not risk his star striker if the title is already secure. Costa has had similar injuries in the past and Mourinho is determined to avoid surgery. Chelsea will likely give Costa an extended break during the season to help him overcome his hamstring problems.

The England C team, which has operated under different names since 1979, is facing the axe as part of the Football Association's spending review. FA chairman Greg Dyke must find £30 million to fund his plan to improve grassroots football and has identified the non-league national team as a potential area of saving. The team, managed by Paul Fairclough and selected from players outside the Football League aged 23 and under, only plays three or four times a year and has not qualified for the semi-finals of the International Challenge Trophy in two years. The team has produced players who have gone on to play for full international teams, but the axe is still hanging over the team due to the difficulty in justifying the cost of running it.

James Haskell, the captain of London Wasps and England flanker, posted a photo of himself dressed up as Iron Man on Instagram, ahead of the release of the new Avengers: Age of Ultron movie. The movie premiered at the Westfield London shopping center in London and was attended by fans who had queued up to see the A-list cast, which includes Robert Downey Jr., Chris Hemsworth, and Scarlett Johansson. Haskell, who returned to Wasps for the 2012 season after spells with Stade Francais, Ricoh Black Rams, and Highlanders in New Zealand, posted the image on Thursday along with the message "Avengers movie is out so thought i would release the inner Iron Man."

A woman defended a Muslim couple on a train in Sydney, Australia, by recording a video of a woman berating them for wearing a hijab. The woman, who is in her 20s, stood up to the ranter and told her to respect the couple. The Muslim couple were "very grateful" for her stand, the woman told Daily Mail Australia. The incident is being investigated by police and Sydney Trains.

A civil lawsuit is being filed against former New England Patriots player Aaron Hernandez by the mother of a man he was convicted of murdering. The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages and Ursula Ward, the mother of Odin Lloyd, plans to ask Hernandez directly why he killed her son at a civil trial. Hernandez was already paid $40m by the Patriots before he was convicted for Lloyd's murder in 2013. The team had already been dismissed from the lawsuit, but if it is determined that they owe Hernandez more money, it will be seized and given to the Lloyd family. Ward's lawyer, Doug Sheff, also plans to call Patriots officials, including owner Bob Kraft, to testify if he believes it is relevant to the case.

Britain has discovered oil in the Falkland Islands, which is likely to increase tensions with Argentina over the ownership of the territory. The Argentine government claims that companies operating off the Falklands coast are acting "illegally" in Argentine territory. The Minister in charge of the Malvinas has said that the discovery will increase the environmental risk and has warned that the "rhetoric and sabre-rattling" from Argentina will get worse. Oil expert Charlie Sharp called the discovery an "excellent start to the exploration campaign." While some shares in oil-exploration companies increased after the announcement, it also caused a rise in the oil price, and there are fears that the Row could escalate. The British government pledged to invest £180 million over the next ten years in defending the islands, including the upgrade of a surface-to-air missile system and the deployment of two Chinook helicopters. The latest discovery comes exactly 33 years after Argentina invaded the Falklands, and the South American state still claims territorial rights to the islands. Defence Secretary Michael Fallon has warned of a "very live threat" from Argentina. Meanwhile, documents released by Edward Snowden allege that Britain was actively spying on Argentina between 2006 and 2011.

A disabled three-legged cat named Freeman was mauled to death by two dogs in a brutal attack that was captured on CCTV in Tarring, West Sussex. The person who owned the dogs did not check on the condition of the cat after the attack, and a woman in a blue car was seen calling the dogs before leaving the scene. Freeman's owner, a 44-year-old mother of three, was devastated by the loss of her family pet. A police investigation is underway to locate the dog owners and determine if they acted appropriately after the attack.

A Chinese woman named Zhu Diandian has become an internet sensation after sharing photos of her life with her pet pig, Five Flowers. She has raised Five Flowers since it was a piglet and the pig has grown to 187lbs (13st). Zhu and Five Flowers often sleep together and she even dresses the pig and takes it for walks. Zhu's husband is reportedly 'tolerant' of the relationship but their pet dog is not as fond of the pig and often looks enviously through a baby gate. Zhu works at a publishing company in Beijing and has almost 40,000 followers on Weibo. Her latest photos of Five Flowers in bed have received over 13,000 'retweets' and almost 9,000 comments.
